docs.snippet: A whistle-blower’s report has alarmed the intelligence agencies’ watchdog. Why won’t the administration share it with Congress?
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s not every day that a whistle-blower in the intelligence community files a complaint about the president of the United States. But it seems to have happened last month, when an unidentified intelligence employee alerted the inspector general of the intelligence community, Michael Atkinson, to multiple acts by President Trump, including a promise he is said to have made to a foreign leader during a phone call.

docs.snippet: The long-awaited spectacle that relaunched the Théâtre du Châtelet was cheerful, but disappointing.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — You might call it a French welcome. On the day the venerable Théâtre du Châtelet was scheduled to reopen after a two-and-a-half-year renovation, Paris’s public transportation system was paralyzed by a strike. The much-hyped street procession to celebrate the venue’s makeover attracted only a thin crowd; inside the auditorium for the first stage performance, there were even some empty seats.
docs.abstract: The long-awaited spectacle that relaunched the Théâtre du Châtelet was cheerful, but disappointing.

docs.snippet: Maybe because the real footage seems insufficient to what we feel in an apocalyptic age.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s a scene that manages to feel both shocking and familiar at once. There’s a camera held up to a car windshield and, outside it, a standard-looking highway, cars and trucks driving by as if all were normal. Beyond the road, flames eat up a hillside and smoke fills the sky. We can hear the voice of the person in the car, and though we might not understand the language, we understand the emotion. The filmmaker, recording an experience because it feels impossible to believe or describe, is freaking out.
docs.abstract: Maybe because the real footage seems insufficient to what we feel in an apocalyptic age.
